#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:10
msgid "Ruby"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:12
msgid ""
"Like Perl, Python, and R, Ruby has its own build system for installing Ruby "
"gems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:17
msgid "Phases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:19
msgid ""
"The ``RubyBuilder`` and ``RubyPackage`` base classes provide the following "
"phases that can be overridden:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:22
msgid "``build`` - build everything needed to install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:23
msgid "``install`` - install everything from build directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:25
msgid "For packages that come with a ``*.gemspec`` file, these phases run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:27
msgid ""
"$ gem build *.gemspec\n"
"$ gem install *.gem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:33
msgid "For packages that come with a ``Rakefile`` file, these phases run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:35
msgid ""
"$ rake package\n"
"$ gem install *.gem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:41
msgid ""
"For packages that come pre-packaged as a ``*.gem`` file, the build phase is "
"skipped and the install phase runs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:44
msgid "$ gem install *.gem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:49
msgid "These are all standard ``gem`` commands and can be found by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:51
msgid "$ gem help commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:56
msgid ""
"For packages that only distribute ``*.gem`` files, these files can be "
"downloaded with the ``expand=False`` option in the ``version`` directive. "
"The build phase will be automatically skipped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:62
msgid "Important files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:64
msgid ""
"When building from source, Ruby packages can be identified by the presence "
"of any of the following files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:67
msgid "``*.gemspec``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:68
msgid "``Rakefile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:69
msgid "``setup.rb`` (not yet supported)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:71
msgid ""
"However, not all Ruby packages are released as source code. Some are only "
"released as ``*.gem`` files. These files can be extracted using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:74
msgid "$ gem unpack *.gem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:81
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:83
#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:97
#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:118
msgid "The ``*.gemspec`` file may contain something like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:85
msgid ""
"summary = \"An implementation of the AsciiDoc text processor and publishing "
"toolchain\"\n"
"description = \"A fast, open source text processor and publishing toolchain "
"for converting AsciiDoc content to HTML 5, DocBook 5, and other formats.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:91
msgid "Either of these can be used for the description of the Spack package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:95
msgid "Homepage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:99
msgid "homepage = \"https://asciidoctor.org\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:104
msgid "This should be used as the official homepage of the Spack package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:108
msgid "Build system dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:110
msgid ""
"All Ruby packages require Ruby at build and run-time. For this reason, the "
"base class contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:113
msgid "extends(\"ruby\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:120
msgid "required_ruby_version = \">= 2.3.0\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:125
msgid "This can be added to the Spack package using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:127
msgid "depends_on(\"ruby@2.3.0:\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:134
msgid "Ruby dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:136
msgid ""
"When you install a package with ``gem``, it reads the ``*.gemspec`` file in "
"order to determine the dependencies of the package. If the dependencies are "
"not yet installed, ``gem`` downloads them and installs them for you. This "
"may sound convenient, but Spack cannot rely on this behavior for two reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:142
msgid "Spack needs to be able to install packages on air-gapped networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:144
msgid ""
"If there is no internet connection, ``gem`` can't download the package "
"dependencies. By explicitly listing every dependency in the ``package.py``, "
"Spack knows what to download ahead of time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:148
msgid "Duplicate installations of the same dependency may occur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:150
msgid ""
"Spack supports *activation* of Ruby extensions, which involves symlinking "
"the package installation prefix to the Ruby installation prefix. If your "
"package is missing a dependency, that dependency will be installed to the "
"installation directory of the same package. If you try to activate the "
"package + dependency, it may cause a problem if that package has already "
"been activated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:157
msgid ""
"For these reasons, you must always explicitly list all dependencies. "
"Although the documentation may list the package's dependencies, often the "
"developers assume people will use ``gem`` and won't have to worry about it. "
"Always check the ``*.gemspec`` file to find the true dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:163
msgid "Check for the following clues in the ``*.gemspec`` file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:165
msgid "``add_runtime_dependency``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:167
msgid "These packages are required for installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:169
msgid "``add_dependency``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:171
msgid "This is an alias for ``add_runtime_dependency``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:173
msgid "``add_development_dependency``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:175
msgid ""
"These packages are optional dependencies used for development. They should "
"not be added as dependencies of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:180
msgid "External documentation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../build_systems/rubypackage.rst:182
msgid ""
"For more information on Ruby packaging, see: https://guides.rubygems.org/"
msgstr ""
